3359
01:32:26,600 --> 01:32:28,500
[SPEAKER_00] I mean inflation sustainability

3360
01:32:28,500 --> 01:32:30,300
[SPEAKER_00] before we got in

3361
01:32:30,300 --> 01:32:37,779
[SPEAKER_00] there's a need to have a broad intersocietal debate about the costs and benefits of Euro adoption

3362
01:32:37,779 --> 01:32:52,079
[SPEAKER_00] such debate should result in a firm commitment and support for the Euro from both the general public and the political elites may come in handy as well

3363
01:32:52,079 --> 01:32:53,300
[SPEAKER_00] as well

3364
01:32:53,300 --> 01:32:57,979
[SPEAKER_00] this however doesn't come easy or for free

3365
01:32:57,979 --> 01:33:05,300
[SPEAKER_00] one government term is not enough to achieve this complex task

3366
01:33:05,300 --> 01:33:08,859
[SPEAKER_00] this is a task for the long haul

3367
01:33:08,859 --> 01:33:12,300
[SPEAKER_00] political consensus is therefore essential

3368
01:33:12,300 --> 01:33:15,640
[SPEAKER_00] the pro-integration appetite

3369
01:33:15,640 --> 01:33:25,359
[SPEAKER_00] in my country Slovakia grew out of an era during which Slovakia was on brink of a severe economic and financial crisis

3370
01:33:25,359 --> 01:33:27,739
[SPEAKER_00] as well as international isolation

3371
01:33:27,739 --> 01:33:42,899
[SPEAKER_00] I'm speaking of late 1990s when my country was infamously labeled ugly dougly by the former US secretary for example and it was a wake-up call for us

3372
01:33:42,899 --> 01:33:51,359
[SPEAKER_00] in the former New Year's thanks to the will of the people and commitment of successive governments

3373
01:33:51,359 --> 01:34:00,260
[SPEAKER_00] Slovakia shook off the nasty nickname and became a trusted member of the European Union and the Euro area

3374
01:34:00,260 --> 01:34:04,500
[SPEAKER_00] it was all the work and energy

3375
01:34:04,500 --> 01:34:11,199
[SPEAKER_00] the support for the Euro post-adoption grew even stronger

3376
01:34:11,199 --> 01:34:13,199
[SPEAKER_00] which is a rather uncommon

3377
01:34:13,199 --> 01:34:15,199
[SPEAKER_00] but all more welcome

3378
01:34:15,199 --> 01:34:17,199
[SPEAKER_00] development

3379
01:34:17,199 --> 01:34:19,199
[SPEAKER_00] fulfilling the accession criteria

3380
01:34:19,199 --> 01:34:24,199
[SPEAKER_00] is however not always really not always straightforward

3381
01:34:24,199 --> 01:34:34,199
[SPEAKER_00] from my experience the ERM-2 is a system which is not tailored for the small open catching up economies like ours

3382
01:34:34,199 --> 01:34:40,199
[SPEAKER_00] Slovakia had to revalue its exchange rate parity twice before this year

3383
01:34:40,199 --> 01:34:48,199
[SPEAKER_00] It is not appropriate for economies like ours to linger in the ERM-2 for the too long time

3384
01:34:48,199 --> 01:34:54,199
[SPEAKER_00] What were the main benefits and costs of adapting the Euro?

3385
01:34:54,199 --> 01:35:00,199
[SPEAKER_00] In our case, and it's important to highlight that we joined the Euro at a really very difficult time, a time of crisis

3386
01:35:00,199 --> 01:35:14,199
[SPEAKER_00] With this in mind, Euro adoption had imminent effects both positive and negative

3387
01:35:14,199 --> 01:35:18,199
[SPEAKER_00] Please, we have to travel in time in 2009

3388
01:35:18,199 --> 01:35:22,199
[SPEAKER_00] Switching of currencies led to savings of transactions costs

3389
01:35:22,199 --> 01:35:32,199
[SPEAKER_00] For example, however, it also meant losing the important tool of independent monetary policy

3390
01:35:32,199 --> 01:35:40,199
[SPEAKER_00] Several studies now confirm that had Slovakia kept the floating currency regime during the recession in 2009

3391
01:35:40,199 --> 01:35:48,199
[SPEAKER_00] The economy would have been temporarily better off by roughly 2% of GDP

3392
01:35:48,199 --> 01:35:56,199
[SPEAKER_00] Overall, however, the effects of joining the Eurozone proved to be significantly positive

3393
01:35:56,199 --> 01:36:04,199
[SPEAKER_00] According to our calculations, joined the Euro increased our GDP by more than 10%

3394
01:36:04,199 --> 01:36:12,199
[SPEAKER_00] About two-thirds of this positive effect came even before the actual adoption of the single currency

3395
01:36:12,199 --> 01:36:14,199
[SPEAKER_00] I mean the so-called anticipation effect

3396
01:36:14,199 --> 01:36:26,199
[SPEAKER_00] The total impact of joining the European Union and the Euro was more than 20% of GDP in our case

3397
01:36:26,199 --> 01:36:34,199
[SPEAKER_00] The Euro area membership boosted our exports and accelerated our convergence

3398
01:36:34,199 --> 01:36:42,199
[SPEAKER_00] Perhaps even more importantly, however, by joining the Eurozone, Slovakia got a seat at the table

3399
01:36:42,199 --> 01:36:49,199
[SPEAKER_00] Maybe not at the head of the table, but let's not get into that right now

3400
01:36:49,199 --> 01:37:01,199
[SPEAKER_00] Sitting around that table, like it, no, not, means your voice and importance in Europe gets stronger

3401
01:37:01,199 --> 01:37:10,199
[SPEAKER_00] Rises Slovakia, still a relatively new kid on the block, with a small, open economy, is in many ways

3402
01:37:10,199 --> 01:37:14,199
[SPEAKER_00] A voice that bridges the gap between ins and outs

3403
01:37:14,199 --> 01:37:20,199
[SPEAKER_00] We do understand that the Eurozone has to offer benefits to all its members

3404
01:37:20,199 --> 01:37:23,199
[SPEAKER_00] Even the prospective ones

3405
01:37:23,199 --> 01:37:29,199
[SPEAKER_00] During the crisis, the Euro provided the necessary price stability and collective strength

3406
01:37:29,199 --> 01:37:34,199
[SPEAKER_00] The establishment of the banking union is one of the best examples

3407
01:37:34,199 --> 01:37:41,199
[SPEAKER_00] With the crisis behind us and a window of opportunities slowly closing

3408
01:37:41,199 --> 01:37:49,199
[SPEAKER_00] It's a time to look to the future and complete the missing elements of the Eurozone architecture

3409
01:37:49,199 --> 01:37:56,199
[SPEAKER_00] We must make it more resilient and prosperous for decades to come, for all

3410
01:37:56,199 --> 01:38:03,199
[SPEAKER_00] Make it accessible and attractive for states that we are willing to participate

3411
01:38:03,199 --> 01:38:09,199
[SPEAKER_00] There are several things we need to do in that respect

3412
01:38:09,199 --> 01:38:18,199
[SPEAKER_00] We have to complete the banking union in order to break the bank's sovereign nexus once and for all

3413
01:38:18,199 --> 01:38:30,199
[SPEAKER_00] We have to get the capital markets union up and running to enhance private risk sharing and provide businesses with greater choice of funding

3414
01:38:30,199 --> 01:38:40,199
[SPEAKER_00] And we have to build a fiscal capacity to compensate the loss of national monetary policy with a shield against asymmetric shocks

3415
01:38:40,199 --> 01:38:51,199
[SPEAKER_00] We have to improve our fiscal rule book to make our fiscal rules simpler and more predictable

3416
01:38:51,199 --> 01:38:57,199
[SPEAKER_00] And we have to design a smart and fair enforcement mechanism for these rules

3417
01:38:57,199 --> 01:38:59,199
[SPEAKER_00] And finally, what we have to do?

3418
01:38:59,199 --> 01:39:07,199
[SPEAKER_00] We have to restore the credibility of the no bailout rule and design a sovereign debt restructuring framework

3419
01:39:07,199 --> 01:39:12,199
[SPEAKER_00] Even if some big players feel no love for that

3420
01:39:12,199 --> 01:39:19,199
[SPEAKER_00] This is a package that I do believe contains all the missing pieces of the puzzle

3421
01:39:19,199 --> 01:39:24,199
[SPEAKER_00] It balances the still necessary risk reduction with risk sharing

3422
01:39:24,199 --> 01:39:32,199
[SPEAKER_00] To achieve a full-fledged banking union, reducing risks by resolving legacy issues from the crisis

3423
01:39:32,199 --> 01:39:44,199
[SPEAKER_00] The high level of NPLs and sovereign exposures in domestic banks must go hand in hand with work on setting-ups of EDIS

3424
01:39:44,199 --> 01:39:51,199
[SPEAKER_00] Here, I support the Commission's new proposal on EDIS, which provides a pragmatic way forward

3425
01:39:51,199 --> 01:40:04,199
[SPEAKER_00] On the fiscal front, our rule book needs to be improved, simplified and most importantly credibly enforced

3426
01:40:04,199 --> 01:40:12,199
[SPEAKER_00] If a supervising body is not up for the task, let's give markets the power to decide

3427
01:40:12,199 --> 01:40:19,199
[SPEAKER_00] Here, sovereign debt restructuring framework could help markets to reinforce fiscal discipline

3428
01:40:19,199 --> 01:40:27,199
[SPEAKER_00] As well as provide an orderly way to restructure public debt if it becomes unmanageable

3429
01:40:27,199 --> 01:40:31,199
[SPEAKER_00] However, markets can also be ruthless

3430
01:40:31,199 --> 01:40:37,199
[SPEAKER_00] Thankfully, we can put checks on the market and manage its overreaction

3431
01:40:37,199 --> 01:40:46,199
[SPEAKER_00] Not having control over one's monetary policy can be costly, particularly during a cyclical downturn

3432
01:40:46,199 --> 01:40:56,199
[SPEAKER_00] A centralised fiscal capacity designed to cushion asymmetric shocks would effectively compensate this loss

3433
01:40:56,199 --> 01:41:00,199
[SPEAKER_00] Limiting the potential market backlash

3434
01:41:00,199 --> 01:41:03,199
[SPEAKER_00] Several instruments have been proposed

3435
01:41:03,199 --> 01:41:11,199
[SPEAKER_00] As I like to say, it doesn't matter what is the colour of the umbrella as long as it stops the rain

3436
